Subject: abnormal seminiferous tubule epithelium morphology [MP:0011750]
Value: any structural anomaly of the stratified epithelial lining of the seminiferous tubules, consisting of the developing spermatozoa and the supporting Sertoli cells, which are tall, columnar type cells that line the tubule

Subject: abnormal X-Y chromosome synapsis during male meiosis [MP:0011751]
Value: an anomaly in the process in which the side by side pairing and physical juxtaposition of X and Y chromosomes is created at the metaphase plate, usually resulting in incorrect sex chromosome disjunction

Subject: abnormal X-Y chromosome synaptonemal complex assembly during male meiosis [MP:0011752]
Value: an anomaly in the process in which forms the structure that holds the X and Y chomosomes together during prophase I of male meiosis and results in exchange of X and Y chromatin during prophase I, or results in exchange of X and Y chromatin outside the chromatin associated with the pseudoautosomal region

Subject: decreased podocyte number [MP:0011753]
Value: reduced number of the modified epithelial cells of the visceral layer of the Bowman capsule in the renal corpuscle

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct intercalated cell morphology [MP:0011754]
Value: any structural anomaly of any of the functionally distinct subtypes of cells (alpha or beta) found on the kidney collecting duct epithelium that regulate acid-base homeostasis and play an important role in the kidney's response to acidosis and alkalosis; alpha-intercalated cells secrete acid whereas beta-intercalated cells secrete base; metabolic acidosis results in the conversion of beta- cells to alpha-intercalated cells giving the kidney a greater ability to secrete protons and return pH to the normal range

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct alpha-intercalated cell morphology [MP:0011755]
Value: any structural anomaly of the tall, columnar epithelial cells found on the kidney collecting duct epithelium which secrete acid (via an apical H+-ATPase and H+/K+ exchanger) in the form of hydrogen ions and reabsorb bicarbonate (via band 3, a basolateral Cl-/HCO3- exchanger);damage to the alpha-intercalated cell's ability to secrete acid can result in distal renal tubular acidosis

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct beta-intercalated cell morphology [MP:0011756]
Value: any structural anomaly of the shorter, flatter cells found on the kidney collecting duct epithelium which secrete bicarbonate (via pendrin, a specialized apical Cl-/HCO3- exchanger) and reabsorb acid (via a basal H+-ATPase)

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct principal cell morphology [MP:0011757]
Value: any structural abnormality of the cuboidal epithelial cells found in the collecting ducts of the kidney which regulate sodium and potassium balance via channels located on the cells apical membrane. Aldosterone increases the number of Na+/K+-ATPase pumps that allow increased sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion whereas antidiuretic hormone (vasopressin) determines the expression of aquaporin channels on the cell surface; together, aldosterone and vasopressin let the principal cell control the quantity of water that is reabsorbed

Subject: renal ischemia [MP:0011758]
Value: inadequate blood flow to one or both kidneys, or nephrons, usually due to functional constriction or actual obstruction of a blood vessel; a significant cause of renal dysfunction and cortical and medullary necrosis

Subject: absent Rathke\'s pouch [MP:0011759]
Value: absence of the diverticulum arsing from the embryonic buccal cavity from which the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland is developed

Subject: abnormal ureteric bud tip morphology [MP:0011760]
Value: any structural anomaly of the terminal ends of the ureteric tree; the ureteric tip cells are proliferating immature cells located at the branching points that induce the adjacent cap mesenchyme to undergo nephrogenesis

Subject: abnormal ureteric bud trunk morphology [MP:0011761]
Value: any structural anomaly of the ureteric bud cells that elongate to form a rigid structure (stalk) consisting of polarized epithelial cells without branching; the stalks differentiate into the collecting system of the mature kidney, while the tip cells interact with the adjacent cells of the metanephric mesenchyme, inducing their conversion into nephrons

Subject: renal/urinary system inflammation [MP:0011762]
Value: local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes in the renal/urinary system; may involve inflammation of the urethra, urinary bladder, ureters or kidneys

Subject: urethritis [MP:0011763]
Value: local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes in the urethra, usually caused by an infection

Subject: ureteritis [MP:0011764]
Value: local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes in a ureter, usually caused by infection or by the mechanic irritation of a stone; the epithelial reaction may be cystic if the reaction is liquefaction, or glandular if the epithelial reaction is by metaplasia

Subject: oroticaciduria [MP:0011765]
Value: increased level of orotic acid, an intermediate of pyrimidine synthesis, in the urine

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder mucosa morphology [MP:0011766]
Value: any structural anomaly of the mucous membrane lining the urinary bladder

Subject: ureterocele [MP:0011767]
Value: saccular dilation of the terminal portion of the ureter that protrudes into the lumen of the urinary bladder, probably due to a congenital stenosis of the ureteric orifice meatus; most often associated with a duplicated collection system, where two ureters drain their respective kidney instead of one

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder trigone morphology [MP:0011768]
Value: any structural anomaly of the smooth triangular region of the wall of the urinary bladder formed by the two ureteral orifices and the internal urethral orifice; it is an area in which the muscle fibers are closely adherent to the mucosa

Subject: urinary bladder fibrosis [MP:0011769]
Value: invasion of fibrous connective tissue into the urinary bladder, often resulting from inflammation or injury

Subject: increased urine selenium level [MP:0011770]
Value: greater than normal amount of selenium in the urine

Subject: abnormal genital tubercle morphology [MP:0011771]
Value: any structural anomaly of the embryonic anlage of the external genitalia, which emerges as paired swellings ventral to the cloacal membrane, is proposed to be derived from all three germ layers, and gives rise to the penis, clitoris, scrotum, labia, and foreskin; GT development is indistinguishable in male and female mouse embryos until approximately E16, when the urethral plate begins to be masculinized to form the penile urethra, marking the beginning of an androgen-dependent phase of sexual differentiation

Subject: genital tubercle hypoplasia [MP:0011772]
Value: underdevelopment or reduced size of the embryonic anlage of the external genitalia, usually due to a reduced number of cells

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder blood vessel morphology [MP:0011773]
Value: any structural anomaly of the network of tubes that carries blood through the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder detrusor smooth muscle morphology [MP:0011774]
Value: any structural anomaly of the bundles of smooth muscle fibers forming the muscular wall of the urinary bladder, which are arranged in a longitudinal and a circular layer and, on contraction, serve to expel urine

Subject: rectal atresia [MP:0011775]
Value: congenital absence, closure, or constriction of the lumen of the terminal portion of the intestinal tube adjacent to the anus, leading to abdominal distention after birth

Subject: abnormal male urethra morphology [MP:0011776]
Value: any structural anomaly of the male fibromuscular tubular canal which extends from the internal urethral orifice in the urinary bladder to the external urethral orifice at the tip of the penis and provides an exit for urine as well as semen during ejaculation; the male urethra is longer than the urethra of females and comprises three major portions, the (i) prostatic, (ii) membranous (aka intermediate), and (iii) cavernous (aka spongy or penile)

Subject: abnormal male prostatic urethra morphology [MP:0011777]
Value: any structural anomaly of the widest and most dilatable part of the male urethra canal which runs almost vertically through the prostate from its base to its apex, lying nearer its anterior than its posterior surface; this portion of the urethral canal is spindle-shaped, being wider in the middle than at either extremity, and narrowest below, where it joins the membranous portion; it is lined by transitional epithelium and contains in its posterior wall, or floor, the orifices of the prostatic utricle, ejaculatory ducts, and prostatic ducts, collectively known as the seminal colliculus (aka verumontanum)

Subject: abnormal male membranous urethra morphology [MP:0011778]
Value: any structural anomaly of the shortest, least dilatable, and, with the exception of the external orifice, the narrowest part of the male urethral canal located in the deep perineal pouch and lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium; it extends downward and forward, with a slight anterior concavity, between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the urethra, perforating the urogenital diaphragm below and behind the pubic symphysis; the membranous portion of the urethra is completely surrounded by the fibers of the sphincter urethrae membranaceae; on either side near its termination are the bulbourethral glands

Subject: abnormal male spongy urethra morphology [MP:0011779]
Value: any structural anomaly of the that longest part of the male urethra contained in the corpus spongiosum and extending from the end of the membranous portion to the external urethral orifice; commencing below the inferior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm it passes forward and upward to the front of the symphysis pubis; and then, in the flaccid condition of the penis, it bends downward and forward; while narrow and of uniform size in the body of the penis, it is dilated behind, within the bulb, and again anteriorly within the glans penis, where it forms the fossa navicularis urethrae; the spongy urethra is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium proximally, and by stratified squamous epithelium distally

Subject: abnormal female urethra morphology [MP:0011780]
Value: any structural anomaly of the short and relatively simple female fibromuscular tubular canal which extends from the urinary bladder outlet to the perineum adjacent to the anterior wall of the vagina, and opens in the vestibule of the vagina posterior to the clitoris and anterior to the vaginal orifice; small mucus urethral glands (Skene's glands) open along its entire length and drain into a single paraurethral duct, which empties at the lateral margin of the external urethral orifice: its epithelial lining changes from transitional epithelium at the bladder end to non-keratinizing stratified squamous epithelium distally

Subject: abnormal bulbourethral gland physiology [MP:0011781]
Value: any functional anomaly of the small paired racemose (compound tubulo-alveolar) glands below the apex of the prostate in males, located posterolateral to the membranous portion of the urethra at the base of the penis, which produce a clear, salty, viscous secretion known as pre-ejaculate (aka as pre-ejaculatory fluid, preseminal fluid, or Cowper's fluid) upon sexual stimulation; this fluid is believed to lubricate the urethra for spermatozoa to pass through and neutralize traces of acidic urine in the urethra

Subject: abnormal internal urethral orifice morphology [MP:0011782]
Value: any structural anomaly of the usually crescent-shaped opening of the urinary bladder into the urethra, placed at the anteroinferior angle (apex) of the urinary bladder trigone

Subject: abnormal ureteral orifice morphology [MP:0011783]
Value: any structural anomaly of the slit-like opening of either ureter into the bladder; normally, the two ureteral orifices are placed at the posterolateral angles of the urinary bladder trigone while the internal urethral orifice is placed at its anteroinferior angle (apex); wide gaping usually indicates vesicoureteral reflux

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder neck morphology [MP:0011784]
Value: any structural anomaly of the constricted portion of the urinary bladder, formed by the meeting of its inferolateral surfaces proximal to the opening of the urethra

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder fundus morphology [MP:0011785]
Value: any structural anomaly of the base or posterior surface of the urinary bladder, which contains the trigone of the bladder and the outlet where urine empties through the internal urethral orifice

Subject: rectourethral fistula [MP:0011786]
Value: an abnormal anatomical passage connecting the urethra and the rectum

Subject: abnormal Bartholin\'s gland morphology [MP:0011787]
Value: any structural anomaly of the paired glands located slightly posterior and to the left and right of the opening of the vagina in the superficial perineal pouch in females; they secrete mucus to lubricate the vagina and are homologous to bulbourethral (Cowper's) glands in males

Subject: absent urethra [MP:0011788]
Value: absence or failure to form of any part of the male or female urethra

Subject: increased urethra carcinoma incidence [MP:0011789]
Value: greater than the expected number of malignant neoplasms arising from the epithelial lining of the urethra in a given population in a given time period

Subject: increased urethral gland adenocarcinoma incidence [MP:0011790]
Value: greater than the expected number of malignant neoplasms arising from urothelial lining or surrounding glands of the urethra in a given population in a given time period

Subject: increased bulbourethral gland adenocarcinoma incidence [MP:0011791]
Value: greater than the expected number of malignant neoplasm of epithelial cells in the bulbourethral glands, usually with a glandular organization in a given population in a given time period

Subject: abnormal urethral gland morphology [MP:0011792]
Value: any structural anomaly of any of the numerous small mucous-secreting glands located in the wall of the male or female urethra that help protect the epithelium from the corrosive urine

Subject: abnormal female urethral gland morphology [MP:0011793]
Value: any structural anomaly of the numerous mucous-secreting glands found in several female mammalian species (including rodents and humans) on the anterior wall of the vagina, around the lower end of the urethra, and possessing a common paraurethral duct which opens (on each side) near the external urethral orifice; they are homologous with the prostate gland in males, have highly variable anatomy, and are believed to be the source of the female ejaculate, a lubricating fluid with a similar consistency to male prostatic fluid that is expelled through the urethra during sexual stimulation; like the male prostate, these glands are susceptible to infection (skenitis), cyst development, and cancer

Subject: abnormal male urethral gland morphology [MP:0011794]
Value: any structural anomaly of any of the numerous small mucous-secreting glands located in the wall of the penile urethra

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder development [MP:0011795]
Value: incomplete or aberrant differentiation of the distensible musculomembranous organ situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion

Subject: abnormal external urethral orifice morphology [MP:0011796]
Value: any structural anomaly of the external opening or orifice of the urethra through which urine and seminal fluid (in males only) leave the body; in males the meatus presents as a vertical slit normally positioned at the tip of glans penis; in females the meatus is located either within the clitoris or between the clitoris and the vagina in the vulvular vestibule of the female genitalia, depending on the species

Subject: blind ureter [MP:0011797]
Value: a ureter ending in a blind-ended segment or pouch

Subject: abnormal urinary bladder weight [MP:0011798]
Value: anomaly in the average weight of the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys compared to controls

Subject: increased urinary bladder weight [MP:0011799]
Value: greater than average weight of the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys compared to controls

Subject: decreased urinary bladder weight [MP:0011800]
Value: less than average weight of the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys compared to controls

Subject: urethra obstruction [MP:0011801]
Value: any impediment or blockage of the canal through which urine is discharged from the bladder in most mammals and through which semen is discharged in the male; usually caused by calculus, or plugs composed of proteinaceous material, cellular debris and possibly crystals

Subject: seminal vesiculitis [MP:0011802]
Value: local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes in the seminal vesicle(s), usually caused by an infection

Subject: double kidney pelvis [MP:0011803]
Value: duplication of the funnel shaped proximal portion of the ureter that is formed by convergence of the major calices

Subject: increased cell migration [MP:0011804]
Value: increased or faster movement of cells from one site to another, often occurring during developmental or chemotactic processes

Subject: decreased cell migration [MP:0011805]
Value: reduced or slower movement of cells from one site to another, often occurring during developmental or chemotactic processes

Subject: decreased dermal fibroblast proliferation [MP:0011806]
Value: reduction in the expansion rate of a dermal fibroblast cell population by cell division

Subject: decreased lung fibroblast proliferation [MP:0011807]
Value: reduction in the expansion rate of a lung fibroblast cell population by cell division

Subject: abnormal myoblast differentiation [MP:0011808]
Value: anomaly in the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myoblast, a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into striated muscle fibers

Subject: abnormal anoikis [MP:0011809]
Value: anomaly in the apoptosis response triggered by inadequate or inappropriate adherence to substrate e.g. after disruption of the interactions between normal epithelial cells and the extracellular matrix

Subject: increased anoikis [MP:0011810]
Value: increase in the apoptosis response triggered by inadequate or inappropriate adherence to substrate e.g. after disruption of the interactions between normal epithelial cells and the extracellular matrix

Subject: decreased anoikis [MP:0011811]
Value: reduction in the apoptosis response triggered by inadequate or inappropriate adherence to substrate e.g. after disruption of the interactions between normal epithelial cells and the extracellular matrix

Subject: increased cranium length [MP:0011812]
Value: having an increased dorsal-to-ventral distance of the cranium

Subject: long maxilla [MP:0011813]
Value: increased length of the upper jaw bone

Subject: abnormal pre-pro B cell morphology [MP:0011814]
Value: any structural anomaly of a pro-B cell that CD45R/B220-positive, CD43-positive, HSA-low, BP-1-negative and Ly6c-negative. This cell type is also described as being lin-negative, AA4-positive, Kit-positive, IL7Ra-positive and CD45R-positive

Subject: increased pre-pro B cell number [MP:0011815]
Value: increased number of pro-B cells that are CD45R/B220-positive, CD43-positive, HSA-low, BP-1-negative and Ly6c-negative; this cell type is also described as being lin-negative, AA4-positive, Kit-positive, IL7Ra-positive and CD45R-positive

Subject: decreased pre-pro B cell number [MP:0011816]
Value: reduced number of pro-B cells that are CD45R/B220-positive, CD43-positive, HSA-low, BP-1-negative and Ly6c-negative; this cell type is also described as being lin-negative, AA4-positive, Kit-positive, IL7Ra-positive and CD45R-positive

Subject: absent pre-pro B cells [MP:0011817]
Value: absence of pro-B cells that are CD45R/B220-positive, CD43-positive, HSA-low, BP-1-negative and Ly6c-negative; this cell type is also described as being lin-negative, AA4-positive, Kit-positive, IL7Ra-positive and CD45R-positive

Subject: abnormal pancreatic beta cell proliferation [MP:0011818]
Value: anomaly in the ability of the cells that secrete insulin and are located towards the center of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: increased pancreatic beta cell proliferation [MP:0011819]
Value: increase in the ability of the cells that secrete insulin and are located towards the center of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: decreased pancreatic beta cell proliferation [MP:0011820]
Value: reduction in the ability of the cells that secrete insulin and are located towards the center of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: abnormal CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cell proliferation [MP:0011821]
Value: anomaly in the ability of the CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell with memory phenotype indicated by being CD45RO and CD127-positive, or also described as being CD25-negative, CD44-high, and CD122- high, to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: increased CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cell proliferation [MP:0011822]
Value: increase in the ability of the a CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell with memory phenotype indicated by being CD45RO and CD127-positive, or also described as being CD25-negative, CD44-high, and CD122- high, to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: decreased CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cell proliferation [MP:0011823]
Value: reduction in the ability of the a CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell with memory phenotype indicated by being CD45RO and CD127-positive, or also described as being CD25-negative, CD44-high, and CD122- high, to undergo expansion by cell division

Subject: increased cell chemotaxis [MP:0011824]
Value: increase in the directed movement response of a motile cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient; movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis)

Subject: decreased cell chemotaxis [MP:0011825]
Value: reduction in the directed movement response of a motile cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient; movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis)

Subject: increased lymphocyte chemotaxis [MP:0011826]
Value: any anomaly in the directed movement of a lymphocyte in response to an external stimulus

Subject: impaired neuron differentiation [MP:0011827]
Value: decreased production of or inability to produce the mature cells of the nervous system that receive, conduct, and transmit impulses

Subject: urinary bladder cysts [MP:0011828]
Value: abnormal membranous pouches or sacs usually filled with a fluid or viscous substance found along the internal lining of the urinary bladder

Subject: vesicovaginal fistula [MP:0011829]
Value: an abnormal fistulous tract extending between the bladder and the vagina, with resulting leakage of urine into the vaginal cavity

Subject: ectopic hair follicle melanin granules [MP:0011830]
Value: any aberration in normal location of pigment granules in the hair follicle that results in variation from expected hair color

Subject: abnormal visual contrast sensitivity [MP:0011831]
Value: any abnormality in the ability to distinguish between increments of light versus dark

Subject: abnormal visual acuity [MP:0011832]
Value: any abnormality in the spatial resolution or resolving power of the visual processing system

Subject: abnormal cremaster muscle morphology [MP:0011833]
Value: any structural anomaly of the thin layer of skeletal muscle that envelops the spermatic cord and testis of most male mammals in a series of loops; it is a continuation of the obliquus internus, arising from the inguinal ligament and inserting into the crest of the pubis and into the sheath of the rectus abdominis; it is innervated by the genital branch of the genitofemoral nerve and functions to draw the testis up toward the superficial inguinal ring in response to cold or to stimulation of the nerve; in females it is represented by only a few muscle loops that envelop the round ligament of the uterus

Subject: abnormal female preputial gland morphology [MP:0011834]
Value: any structural anomaly of the paired, lobulated, modified sebaceous glands located on the side of the clitoris in female rodents; in contrast to the preputial glands in male rodents, clitoral glands are a minor source of olfactory stimuli contributing to sexual attractivity; unlike other sebaceous glands, they undergo progressive atrophy of the glandular portion with marked ductal ectasia as rodents age; there is no true anatomical equivalent in humans

Subject: abnormal urogenital fold morphology [MP:0011835]
Value: any structural anomaly of the pair of folds derived from the cloacal folds which give rise to a portion of the external genitalia; in male embryos they close over the urethral plate and fuse to form the spongy (penile) urethra and ventral aspect of the penis, not including the glans; failure of fusion of the urethral folds leads to hypospadias; in female embryos they fuse only anterior to the anus and form the labia minora

Subject: abnormal cloacal fold morphology [MP:0011836]
Value: any structural anomaly of the pair of mesenchymal swellings (folds) located on either side of the cloacal membrane during the indifferent stage of embryonic development; cranial to the cloacal membrane the folds unite to form the genital tubercle; caudally the folds are subdivided into urogenital folds anteriorly and anal folds posteriorly

Subject: abnormal cloacal membrane morphology [MP:0011837]
Value: any structural anomaly of the membrane that covers the embryonic cloaca, formed by the union of proctodeal (anal pit) ectoderm and cloacal endoderm, with no intervening mesoderm; the urorectal septum joins the cloacal membrane and divides it into an anal membrane and a urogenital membrane; the point where the urorectal septum intersects the cloacal membrane is the future site of the perineal body; proliferation of mesoderm and ectoderm around the cloacal membrane produces primordial tissues of the external genitalia in both sexes: the genital tubercle, genital folds, and genital swellings

Subject: abnormal navicular fossa morphology [MP:0011838]
Value: any structural anomaly of the dilated terminal portion of the male spongy urethra located in the glans penis right before the external urethral orifice, also referred to as the most distal pendulous urethra; it is lined by stratified squamous, non-keratinizing epithelium; during development, the glans of the penis is initially solid but cannulates to give rise to the navicular fossa

Subject: abnormal Guerin\'s valve morphology [MP:0011839]
Value: any structural anomaly of the fold or valve of mucus membrane on the upper wall of the navicuar fossa

Subject: abnormal urethral crest morphology [MP:0011840]
Value: any structural anomaly of the longitudinal mucosal fold in the dorsal wall of the urethra

Subject: abnormal male urethral crest morphology [MP:0011841]
Value: any structural anomaly of the narrow longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the male urethra, extending from the uvula of the bladder through the prostatic urethra; when distended, it may serve to prevent the passage of the semen backward into the bladder; on either side of the male urethral crest is a slightly depressed fossa, the prostatic sinus, the floor of which is perforated by the orifices of the prostatic ducts from the lateral lobes of the prostate; the ducts of the middle lobe open behind the crest; at the forepart of the crest, below its summit, is a median elevation, the colliculus seminalis, upon or within the margins of which are the orifices of the prostatic utricle and the slit-like openings of the ejaculatory ducts

Subject: abnormal female urethral crest morphology [MP:0011842]
Value: any structural anomaly of the conspicuous longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the female urethra

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct epithelium morphology [MP:0011843]
Value: any structural anomaly of the simple cuboidal epithelium lining the lumen of kidney collecting ducts; the mature and differentiated CD epithelium comprises two unique cells types with principal cells responsible for vasopressin-regulated water reabsorption, and intercalated cells regulating acid-base homeostasis; injury to the epithelium is believed to cause epithelial cells to acquire mesenchymal characteristics via epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT), a process through which tubular epithelial cells may transform into interstitial fibroblasts and promote renal fibrosis

Subject: kidney collecting duct atrophy [MP:0011844]
Value: acquired diminution of the size of the kidney collecting ducts associated with wasting as from death and reabsorbtion of cells, diminished cellular proliferation, decreased cellular volume, pressure, ischemia, malnutrition, reduced function or malfunction, or hormonal changes

Subject: abnormal kidney collecting duct number [MP:0011845]
Value: anomaly in the number of any of the kidney ducts that collect urine from the distal convoluted tubules, merge and become larger as they descend from the renal cortex into the medulla, and respond to vasopressin and aldosterone to regulate water, electrolyte and acid-base balance

Subject: decreased kidney collecting duct number [MP:0011846]
Value: smaller than expected number of the kidney ducts that collect urine from the distal convoluted tubules, merge and become larger as they descend from the renal cortex into the medulla, and respond to vasopressin and aldosterone to regulate water, electrolyte and acid-base balance

Subject: increased kidney collecting duct number [MP:0011847]
Value: larger than expected number of the kidney ducts that collect urine from the distal convoluted tubules, merge and become larger as they descend from the renal cortex into the medulla, and respond to vasopressin and aldosterone to regulate water, electrolyte and acid-base balance

Subject: abnormal vagina vestibule morphology [MP:0011848]
Value: any structural anomaly of the space posterior to the glans clitoridis, between the labia minora; located within the vestibule are the openings of the vagina, the urethra, and the ducts of the lesser vestibular glands, the greater vestibular (Bartholin's) glands, and the paraurethral (Skene's) glands, which release mucus into the vestibule to maintain a moist, lubricated vestibular environment; the vestibule is also moistened by secretions from the cervical mucus glands located in the inferior region of the uterus

Subject: abnormal clitoral bone morphology [MP:0011849]
Value: any structural anomaly of the ossified region of endochondral and membranous bone located in the clitoris of most mammals except humans;it is homologous to the penile bone (aka as baculum, penis bone or os penis) in male mammals

Subject: absent clitoral bone [MP:0011850]
Value: absence of the unique bone located in the clitoris of most mammals except humans

Subject: abnormal embryonic cloaca development [MP:0011851]
Value: failure or anomaly in the formation of a pouch-like dilation of the caudal end of the hindgut by the process of folding of the caudal region of the embryonic disk; during the tail-fold process, the posteriorly placed allantois, or allantoic diverticulum of the yolk sac, becomes an anterior extension of the cloaca; soon after the cloaca forms, it receives posterolaterally the caudal ends of the paired mesonephric ducts and hence becomes a junctional cistern for the allantois, the hindgut, and the ducts; a cloacal membrane, composed of ectoderm and endoderm, is the caudal limit of the primitive gut and temporarily separates the cloacal cavity from the extraembryonic confines of the amniotic cavity; subsequent growth of the urorectal septum eventually subdivides the once single cloaca chamber into the primitive urogenital sinus (ventrally) and the anorectal canal of the hindgut (dorsally)

Subject: patent urachus [MP:0011852]
Value: failure of complete urachal lumen closure resulting in an open channel between the urinary bladder and the umbilicus and leakage of urine through the umbilicus

Subject: abnormal urorectal septum morphology [MP:0011853]
Value: any structural anomaly of the ridge of mesoderm covered with endoderm that in the early developing embryo partitions the endodermal cloaca into the primary urogenital sinus (ventrally) and the anorectal canal of the hindgut (dorsally); the urorectal septum eventually fuses with the cloacal membrane, dividing it into a dorsal anal membrane and a larger ventral urogenital membrane - this area of fusion is represented in the adult by the perineal body

Subject: cerebral edema [MP:0011854]
Value: excess accumulation of water in the intra- and/or extracellular spaces of the brain

Subject: abnormal glomerular filtration barrier morphology [MP:0011855]
Value: any structural anomaly of the highly specialized blood filtration interface that displays a high conductance to small and midsized solutes in plasma but retains relative impermeability to macromolecules; its integrity is maintained by physicochemical and signalling interplay among its three core constituents -- the fenestrated endothelium of the glomerular capillaries, the glomerular basement membrane, and the filtration slits of the visceral epithelial cell (podocyte)

Subject: abnormal glomerular filtration barrier function [MP:0011856]
Value: anomaly in the function of the highly specialized blood filtration interface that displays a high conductance to small and midsized solutes in plasma but retains relative impermeability to macromolecules; its integrity is maintained by physicochemical and signalling interplay among its three core constituents -- the fenestrated endothelium of the glomerular capillaries, the glomerular basement membrane, and the filtration slits of the visceral epithelial cell (podocyte); the barrier permits the passage of water, ions, and small molecules from the bloodstream into the Bowman's space and prevents the loss of large and/or negatively charged proteins (e.g. serum albumin) from blood into urine

Subject: short kidney papilla [MP:0011857]
Value: reduced average length of the apex of the renal pyramid that projects into a calyx

Subject: elongated kidney papilla [MP:0011858]
Value: increased average length of the apex of the renal pyramid that projects into a calyx

Subject: decreased renal glomerulus basement membrane thickness [MP:0011859]
Value: reduced width of the layer of extracellular matrix that lies between the endothelium of the glomerular capillaries and the podocytes of the inner or visceral layer of the Bowman capsule

Subject: abnormal peritubular capillary endothelium morphology [MP:0011860]
Value: any structural anomaly of the thin sheet of endothelial cells along the basal lamina of renal tubular cells characterized by their attenuated shape and numerous regularly-spaced transcellular pores (aka fenestrae or fenestrations); the fenestrae of peritubular capillaries differ from the fenestrae of glomerular capillaries in that they are much smaller and possess a small overlying diaphragm

Subject: increased cranium height [MP:0011861]

Subject: detached podocyte [MP:0011869]

Subject: abnormal c wave shape [MP:0012040]
Value: any anomaly in the graphical representation of the c wave in the electroretinogram; the ERG c-wave can be used to assess the functional integrity of the photoreceptors, the pigment epithelial cells and the interactions between them.

Subject: susceptible to pulmonary hyaline membrane formation [MP:0012041]
Value: increased likelihood of the presence of an eosinophilic hyaline (glass-like) material composed of fibrin, proteinaceous exudate and cellular debris, and lining or filling the alveoli, alveolar ducts and bronchioles

Subject: low alcohol preference [MP:0012042]
Value: decreased predilection to ingest alcohol over other substances

Subject: increased myoepithelioma incidence [MP:0012043]
Value: greater than the expected occurrence of a benign tumor of myoepithelial cells, occurring in a specific population in a given time period

Subject: abnormal phospholipase A2 level [MP:0012044]
Value: anomaly in the amount of any of the enzymes that release fatty acids from the second carbon group of glycerol

Subject: increased susceptibility to hypertension [MP:0012045]
Value: more likely than normal to develop sustained high blood pressure at a level that is likely to result in cardiovascular disease and/or other pathological states

Subject: decreased susceptibility to hypertension [MP:0012046]
Value: less likely than normal to develop sustained high blood pressure at a level that is likely to result in cardiovascular disease and/or other pathological states

Subject: abnormal cholinesterase level [MP:0012047]
Value: anomaly in the amount of any of the enzymes that catalyze the hydrolysis of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine into choline and acetic acid

Subject: altered response to retinal ischemic injury [MP:0012048]
Value: altered response to lack of adequate blood flow, due to trauma or disease, to support the normal functioning of the retina

Subject: increased susceptilbility to retinal ischemic injury [MP:0012049]
Value: increased frequency or more severe response, such as necrotic tissue size, to lack of adequate blood flow, due to trauma or disease, to support the normal functioning of the retina

Subject: decreased susceptilbility to retinal ischemic injury [MP:0012050]
Value: decreased frequency or less severe response, such as necrotic tissue size, to lack of adequate blood flow, due to trauma or disease, to support the normal functioning of the retina

Subject: spasticity [MP:0012051]
Value: a motor disorder characterized by a velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone, exaggerated (hyperexcitable) tendon reflexes and increased resistance to stretch

Subject: hypertonicity [MP:0012052]
Value: abnormally increased muscle tone or strength that impairs proper movement

Subject: limb hypertonicity [MP:0012053]
Value: limbs exhibit abnormally increased muscle tone; can be due to muscle genetic defects or some CNS disorders and may be evident in arm or leg deformities

Subject: abnormal phrenic nerve innervation pattern [MP:0012054]
Value: any changes in the placement, morphology or number of phrenic nerve fibers providing motor supply to the diaphragm as well as sensory fibers to the central tendon, or in the thorax, phrenic nerve sensory fibers to the mediastinal pleura and pericardium

Subject: abnormal phrenic nerve innervation pattern to diaphragm [MP:0012055]
Value: any changes in the placement, morphology or number of the portion of phrenic nerve fibers providing motor supply to the diaphragm

Subject: abnormal polar trophectoderm morphology [MP:0012056]
Value: any structural anomaly of the trophectoderm portion that surrounds the inner cell mass (ICM); unlike mural trophectoderm cells which stop proliferating and become large polyploid cells (the primary trophoblastic giant cells) by endoreduplication, polar trophectoderm cells remain diploid, continue to proliferate and give rise to both the ectoplacental cone and the extraembryonic ectoderm

Subject: abnormal mural trophectoderm morphology [MP:0012057]

Subject: abnormal morula morphology [MP:0012058]
Value: any structural anomaly of the globular solid mass of blastomeres formed by cleavage of a zygote that typically precedes the blastula, typically after the zygote has divided into 32 cells

Subject: thick diaphragm muscle [MP:0012059]
Value: increased thickness of the diaphragm muscle

Subject: abnormal diaphragm central tendon morphology [MP:0012061]
Value: any structural anomaly of the three-lobed cloverleaf-shaped aponeurosis situated at the center of the diaphragm; the central tendon is fused with the fibrous pericardium that provides attachment for the muscle fibers

Subject: small tail bud [MP:0012062]
Value: decreased size or area of the primordial region of the embryo that arises to form the tail of the adult

Subject: absent tail bud [MP:0012063]
Value: missing the primordial region of the embryo that arises to form the tail of the adult

Subject: abnormal astrocyte number [MP:0012064]
Value: anomaly in the number of the large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system - the largest and most numerous neuroglial cells in the brain and spinal cord

Subject: increased astrocyte number [MP:0012065]
Value: increase in the number of the large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system - the largest and most numerous neuroglial cells in the brain and spinal cord

Subject: decreased astrocyte number [MP:0012066]
Value: reduction in the number of the large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system - the largest and most numerous neuroglial cells in the brain and spinal cord

Subject: abnormal olfactory gland morphology [MP:0012067]
Value: any structural anomaly of the Bowman's glands (aka glands of Bowman, olfactory glands), situated in the olfactory mucosa, beneath the olfactory epithelium, in the lamina propria, a connective tissue also containing fibroblasts, blood vessels, and bundles of fine axons from the olfactory neurons; Bowman's glands consists of an acinus in the lamina propria and a secretory duct going out through the olfactory epithelium

Subject: abnormal globose cell of olfactory epithelium morphology [MP:0012068]
Value: any structural anomaly of the rounded or elliptical epithelial cells, with pale-staining open face nucleus and pale cytoplasm rich in free ribosomes and clusters of centrioles, that form a distinct basal zone spaced slightly from the basal surface of the olfactory epithelium

Subject: abnormal horizontal basal cell of olfactory epithelium morphology [MP:0012069]
Value: any structural anomaly of the flat or angular epithelial cell with condensed nuclei and darkly staining cytoplasm containing numerous intermediate filaments inserted into desmosomes contacting surrounding supporting cells, that lie in contact with the basal lamina of olfactory epithelium

Subject: altered susceptibility to osteoporosis [MP:0012070]
Value: a change in the likelihood that an organism will develop a reduction in bone mass or atrophy of skeletal tissue, usually accompanied by gross changes to bone matrix, leading to bone fragility

Subject: increased susceptibility to osteoporosis [MP:0012071]
Value: greater likelihood that an organism will develop a reduction in bone mass or atrophy of skeletal tissue, usually accompanied by gross changes to bone matrix, leading to bone fragility

Subject: decreased susceptibility to osteoporosis [MP:0012072]
Value: reduced likelihood that an organism will develop a reduction in bone mass or atrophy of skeletal tissue, usually accompanied by gross changes to bone matrix, leading to bone fragility

Subject: premature mammary gland growth during pregnancy [MP:0012073]
Value: faster progression of the extensive and rapid branching of the mammary ducts, expansion of mammary epithelium in the stroma between the ducts with or without abnormalities in nipple maturation in preparation for lactation

Subject: failure of mammary gland growth during pregnancy [MP:0012074]
Value: arrest, or failure ti initiate the extensive and rapid branching of the mammary ducts, expansion of mammary epithelium in the stroma between the ducts with or without abnormalities in nipple maturation in preparation for lactation

Subject: impaired mammary gland growth during pregnancy [MP:0012075]
Value: defect in the extensive and rapid branching of the mammary ducts, expansion of mammary epithelium in the stroma between the ducts with or without abnormalities in nipple maturation in preparation for lactation

Subject: abnormal agouti pigmentation [MP:0012076]
Value: amount and distribution of yellow pigment (phaeomelanin) relative to black or brown pigment (eumelanin) is variably increased or decreased compared with a wild-type agouti pattern resulting in a range of coat color from yellow to almost black

Subject: webbed neck [MP:0012077]
Value: the skin on the neck appears as loose folds that develop a web-like appearance from the ears to the shoulder during growth and maturation

Subject: abnormal tail ring morphology [MP:0012078]
Value: any structural anomaly of the segmentally patterned skin ridges appearing on the tail of rodents

Subject: abnormal spinal reflex [MP:0012079]
Value: any anomaly in the reflexive action mediated by cells of the spinal cord, or the involuntary movement reaction caused by the application of a stimulus to an organism; these include signals originating from heat from burning, sharp sensations, and other painful feelings

Subject: chylous ascites [MP:0012080]
Value: the extravasation of milky triglyceride-rich chyle into the peritoneal cavity; often a secondary symptom of neoplasms

Subject: absent heart tube [MP:0012081]
Value: absence of the primitive epithelial cardiac tube before the division into the chambers of the mature heart

Subject: delayed heart development [MP:0012082]
Value: late onset of the induction and/or differentiation of the heart

Subject: absent foregut [MP:0012083]
Value: absence of the anterior portion of the primitive digestive tube of the embryo that lies cephalic to the junction of the yolk stalk, consists of endodermal tissue, and gives rise to the pharynx, lower respiratory system, esophagus, stomach, duodenum proximal to the biliary tract, liver, pancreas, biliary tract, and gall bladder

Subject: truncated foregut [MP:0012084]
Value: shortened foregut that terminates abruptly as if having an end or point cut off

Subject: midface hypoplasia [MP:0012085]
Value: underdevelopment of the midfacial region comprising the nasal, maxillary, and zygomatic bones, leading to a concave-looking face

Subject: absent hindgut [MP:0012086]
Value: absence of the caudal portion of the primitive digestive tube of the embryo

Subject: absent midbrain [MP:0012087]
Value: absence of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

Subject: abnormal midbrain size [MP:0012088]
Value: deviation from the average range of midbrain size compared to normal

Subject: decreased midbrain size [MP:0012089]
Value: size reduction or truncation of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

Subject: midbrain hypoplasia [MP:0012090]
Value: underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

Subject: increased midbrain size [MP:0012091]
Value: greater than average size of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

Subject: diencephalon hypoplasia [MP:0012092]
Value: underdevelopment or decreased size, usually due an increased number of cells in the rostral portion of the brain stem

Subject: absent nodal flow [MP:0012093]
Value: absence of the leftward movement of extra-embryonic fluid at the ventral node; nodal flow is autonomously generated by the rotation of cilia that are tilted toward the posterior on cells of the ventral node and is the central process in symmetry breaking on the left-right axis; when nodal cilia are immotile or absent, nodal flow does not occur

Subject: abnormal Reichert\'s membrane thickness [MP:0012094]
Value: anomaly in the width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm

Subject: increased Reichert\'s membrane thickness [MP:0012095]
Value: increased width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm

Subject: decreased Reichert\'s membrane thickness [MP:0012096]
Value: reduced width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm

Subject: abnormal spongiotrophoblast size [MP:0012097]
Value: anomaly in the size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

Subject: increased spongiotrophoblast size [MP:0012098]
Value: greater size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

Subject: decreased spongiotrophoblast size [MP:0012099]
Value: reduction of the size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

Subject: absent spongiotrophoblast [MP:0012100]
Value: absence of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

Subject: acoria [MP:0012101]
Value: absence of the pupil of the eye

Subject: absent trophectoderm [MP:0012102]

Subject: abnormal bilaminar embryonic disk morphology [MP:0012103]
Value: any structural anomaly of the flattened, almost circular bilaminar plate of cells formed when the inner cell mass (aka embryoblast) forms two epithelial layers, each of a distinct lineage, separated by an extracellular basement membrane: the external (dorsal) layer is called the epiblast and the internal (ventral) layer is called the hypoblast (aka primitive endoderm); together, they compose the bilaminar embryonic disc

Subject: small amniotic cavity [MP:0012104]
Value: reduced size of the closed space between the embryo and the amnion which contains the amniotic fluid and is formed by the fusion of the parts of the anterior and posterior amniotic folds

Subject: delayed gastrulation [MP:0012105]
Value: late onset of the development and invagination of the embryonic germ layers

Subject: impaired exercise endurance [MP:0012106]
Value: impaired performance during controlled physical activity

Subject: enhanced exercise endurance [MP:0012107]
Value: improved performance during controlled physical activity

Subject: increased trophoblast glycogen cell number [MP:0012108]
Value: greater number of the glycogen-accumulating trophoblast cells that arise in the junctional zone of the placenta

Subject: decreased trophoblast glycogen cell number [MP:0012109]
Value: reduced number of the glycogen-accumulating trophoblast cells that arise in the junctional zone of the placenta

Subject: increased hair follicle number [MP:0012110]

Subject: failure of morula compaction [MP:0012111]

Subject: increased inner cell mass proliferation [MP:0012112]
Value: enhanced expansion rate of the inner cell mass

Subject: decreased inner cell mass proliferation [MP:0012113]

Subject: absent inner cell mass proliferation [MP:0012114]
Value: absence of expansion of the inner cell mass

Subject: increased trophectoderm apoptosis [MP:0012119]
Value: increase in the number of trophectoderm cells undergoing programmed cell death

Subject: trophectoderm cell degeneration [MP:0012120]

Subject: sclerocornea [MP:0012121]

Subject: abnormal iris transillumination [MP:0012122]
Value: any anomaly in the radial light dispersion pattern of the iris when a focused light beam is passed through it; particular dispersion pattern anomalies are indicative of abnormalities in iris pigment distribution and for the presence of glaucoma, atrophy and/or infection

Subject: abnormal bronchoconstrictive response [MP:0012123]
Value: anomaly in the expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography

Subject: increased bronchoconstrictive response [MP:0012124]
Value: enhanced or greater than expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography

Subject: decreased bronchoconstrictive response [MP:0012125]
Value: reduction in the expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography

Subject: abnormal placenta hemotrichorial membrane morphology [MP:0012126]
Value: any structural anomaly of the three trophoblast cell layers found in rodent placentas between fetal blood vessels and maternal blood sinuses

Subject: absent placenta hemotrichorial membrane [MP:0012127]

Subject: abnormal blastocyst formation [MP:0012128]
Value: atypical formation of a blastocyst from a solid ball of cells known as a morula, including anomalies in the formation of a fluid-filled cavity (blastocoele) and/or initiation of inner cell mass and trophectoderm differentiation

Subject: failure of blastocyst formation [MP:0012129]

Subject: abnormal morula formation [MP:0012130]

Subject: small visceral yolk sac [MP:0012131]

Subject: abnormal midbrain-hindbrain boundary morphology [MP:0012132]

Subject: absent midbrain-hindbrain boundary [MP:0012133]

Subject: absent umbilical cord [MP:0012134]

Subject: embryonic-extraembryonic boundary constriction [MP:0012135]

Subject: absent forebrain [MP:0012136]

Subject: abnormal forebrain size [MP:0012137]

Subject: decreased forebrain size [MP:0012138]

Subject: increased forebrain size [MP:0012139]
Value: greater than average size of the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions)

Subject: forebrain hyperplasia [MP:0012140]
Value: overdevelopment or increased size, usually due to a increased number of cells, of the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions)

Subject: absent hindbrain [MP:0012141]
Value: absence of the part of the brain developed from the posterior of the three primary brain vesicles of the embryonic neural tube from which the metencephalon and myelencephalon are derived; the metencephalon (anterior part of the embryonic hindbrain), gives rise to the cerebellum and pons while the myelencephalon (posterior portion of the embryonic hindbrain) gives rise to the medulla oblongata

Subject: absent amniotic cavity [MP:0012142]
Value: absence of the closed space between the embryo and the amnion which contains the amniotic fluid and is formed by the fusion of the parts of the anterior and posterior amniotic folds

Subject: decreased a wave amplitude [MP:0012143]

Subject: decreased b wave amplitude [MP:0012144]
Value: reduction in the size (height or maximum displacement) of the b wave as measured in the electroretinogram

Subject: increased a wave amplitude [MP:0012145]

Subject: increased b wave amplitude [MP:0012146]

Subject: increased a wave implicit time [MP:0012147]

Subject: decreased a wave implicit time [MP:0012148]

Subject: decreased b wave implicit time [MP:0012149]

Subject: increased b wave implicit time [MP:0012150]

Subject: increased a wave latency [MP:0012151]

Subject: decreased a wave latency [MP:0012152]
Value: decrease in the time from onset of stimulus to beginning of the a wave

Subject: increased b wave latency [MP:0012153]
Value: increase in the time from onset of stimulus to beginning of the b wave

Subject: decreased b wave latency [MP:0012154]
Value: decrease in the time from onset of stimulus to beginning of the b wave

Subject: abnormal optic pit morphology [MP:0012155]
Value: any structural anomaly of either of the two pits that appear bilaterally in the region destined to become the forebrain as the cranial neural folds fuse; these optic pits or sulci continue to deepen laterally and bulge from the two sides of the forebrain to become the optic vesicles

Subject: rostral-caudal axis duplication [MP:0012156]
Value: partial or complete duplication of rostral-caudal axis structures

Subject: rostral body truncation [MP:0012157]

Subject: absent visceral endoderm [MP:0012158]
Value: absence of the primitive endoderm-derived tissue which remains in contact with and surrounds the extra-embryonic ectoderm and the epiblast and provides signals for the differentiation and patterning of the epiblast; a small number of visceral endoderm cells also contribute to the endoderm of the embryonic gut

Subject: absent anterior visceral endoderm [MP:0012159]

Subject: expanded anterior visceral endoderm [MP:0012160]

Subject: absent distal visceral endoderm [MP:0012161]

Subject: absent parietal endoderm [MP:0012162]

Subject: abnormal dental mesenchyme morphology [MP:0012163]

Subject: abnormal conjunctiva goblet cell morphology [MP:0012164]

Subject: absent neural folds [MP:0012165]

Subject: absent neural plate [MP:0012166]

Subject: abnormal epigenetic regulation of gene expression [MP:0012167]

Subject: abnormal optic placode morphology [MP:0012168]

Subject: optic placode degeneration [MP:0012169]

Subject: absent optic placodes [MP:0012170]

Subject: oligohydramnios [MP:0012171]

Subject: abnormal amniotic fluid composition [MP:0012172]

Subject: short rostral-caudal axis [MP:0012173]

Subject: flat head [MP:0012174]

Subject: flat face [MP:0012175]

Subject: abnormal head development [MP:0012176]

Subject: delayed head development [MP:0012177]

Subject: absent frontonasal prominence [MP:0012178]

Subject: abnormal splanchnic mesoderm morphology [MP:0012179]

Subject: abnormal somatic mesoderm morphology [MP:0012180]

Subject: increased somite number [MP:0012181]
Value: increase in the average number of somites formed relative to littermates or other controls

Subject: abnormal presomitic mesoderm morphology [MP:0012182]
Value: any structural anomaly of the unsegmented field of paraxial mesoderm present posterior to the most recently formed somite pair, from which somites will form

Subject: decreased paraxial mesoderm size [MP:0012183]

Subject: absent paraxial mesoderm [MP:0012184]
Value: absence or loss of the mesoderm normally found at either side of the midline embryonic notochord that, on segmentation, forms the paired somites.

Subject: abnormal muscle precursor cell morphology [MP:0012185]

Subject: abnormal muscle precursor cell physiology [MP:0012186]

Subject: abnormal intraembryonic coelom morphology [MP:0012187]

Subject: increased regulatory T cell apoptosis [MP:0012188]

Subject: decreased regulatory T cell apoptosis [MP:0012189]

Subject: increased cytotoxic T cell apoptosis [MP:0012190]

Subject: decreased cytotoxic T cell apoptosis [MP:0012191]

Subject: abnormal keratinocyte migration [MP:0012192]

Subject: increased keratinocyte migration [MP:0012193]

Subject: decreased keratinocyte migration [MP:0012194]

Subject: impaired neural crest cell differentiation [MP:0012195]

Subject: abnormal myofibroblast differentiation [MP:0012196]

Subject: impaired myofibroblast differentiation [MP:0012197]

Subject: absent interphalangeal joint [MP:0012198]

Subject: abnormal interphalangeal joint morphology [MP:0012199]

Subject: increased endothelial cell proliferation [MP:0012200]
Value: greater expansion rate of a endothelial cell population by cell division

Subject: decreased endothelial cell proliferation [MP:0012201]

Subject: abnormal endothelial cell proliferation [MP:0012202]

Subject: abnormal neuronal stem cell morphology [MP:0012203]

Subject: abnormal neuronal stem cell physiology [MP:0012204]
